	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Not strictly emulation dev-related, but close enough...
<br />
<br />I'm researching the history of NES emulation and I thought those of you that actually develop emulators might have a better sense of what came first. On nesworld.com, I found this comment on an outdated page:
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The first NES emulator ever made was coded by a Russian guy, Alex Krasivsky who let Marat Fayzullin (known for other emulators like Virtual Gameboy, Colem, fMSX) have the source code. Marat "fixed" the code and added a lot of different stuff and released in under the name iNES.</div>
<br />
<br />Sound accurate? Did Krasivsky's emulator have a name and was it distributed online?
<br />
<br />Did any Famicom emulators appear in Japan prior to Krasivsky's? When did Pasofami appear on the scene?
<br />
<br />And would everyone agree that NESticle broke NES emulation into the 'mainstream' and helped standardize the iNES format (even more so than iNES itself)? My research suggests so. I'm also amazed how long NESticle has managed to stick around...
<br />
<br />Any info or links are appreciated.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


